justification:
During the second World War, the French city of Le Havre was severely bombed.&amp;nbsp; August Perret, a pioneering French modernist architect, was tasked with rebuilding the city.&amp;nbsp; Perret’s reconstruction is considered exceptional for its seamless integration of the city’s extant historic structures with modern concrete construction and design innovations.&amp;nbsp; Perret’s new buildings for Le Havre were conceived of within a 6.24m square modular system.&amp;nbsp; 
&amp;nbsp;
Apeloig designed this poster in 2006 to commemorate the UNESCO designation of the French city of Le Havre as a World Heritage Site.&amp;nbsp; His design takes Le Havre’s innovative architecture as its subject and Perret’s conception of the city as a Gesamtkustwerk as its framework.&amp;nbsp; Graphic renditions of the standardized facades of three of Perret’s buildings are laid atop one another, each in a different primary color. The areas where the different buildings overlap generate new colors (green and purple), while the text forms echo the windows in which they appear to sit.&amp;nbsp; Apeloig’s poster evokes the harmony of the modular system employed by Perret.
